Preliminaries

The R codes shown in this document are available for download. Save a copy of these codes for use as a template in your own work on the exercises.

The following code chunk loads the packages we’ll need, sets the random seed, and makes some stylistic choices. It also creates a directory to hold some of the graphics files we will be creating.

set.seed(517218506L)
library(tidyverse)
library(phylopomp)
library(gifski)
theme_set(theme_bw())
dir.create("figs")

The Moran process

The earliest phylodynamics methods (Rasmussen, Ratmann, and Koelle 2011; Volz, Kosakovsky Pond, Ward, Leigh Brown, and Frost 2009) were based on the so-called Kingman coalescent (Kingman 1982b, 1982a). The Kingman coalescent is a stochastic process that generates genealogies. It is typically viewed backward in time, as a process whereby lineages coalesce at random times.

In its simplest form, it has only two parameter, a population size, \(n\), and a coalescence rate, \(\mu\).

Interestingly, the coalescent is related to another classical model of population genetics, the so-called Moran process (King, Lin, and Ionides 2020; Moran 1958). The Moran process is very easily described: A population of \(n\) individuals experiences random events at rate \(\mu\). At each event, a random member of the population gives birth to a new lineage. Simultaneously, a second random member of the population dies. Thus the population size remains constant. All the members of the population are equally likely to be selected for either of these two roles: they are said to be exchangeable.

King et al. (2020) show how one can make this connection precise. In particular, they show how one can simulate the Moran genealogy process. The simulator is implemented as part of the phylopomp package. Here is the help page relevant to the Moran genealogy process (obtained by executing ?moran in an R session).

The following codes simulate the Moran genealogy process for 10 time units (the unit of time is such that \(\mu=1\)). The first call to simulate returns an object of class gpsim. The second line plots this object as a tree. Calling simulate again on a gpsim object continues the simulation.

simulate("Moran",time=0,n=10,psi=0) -> m
m |> plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+expand_limits(x=5)
m |> simulate("Moran",time=1) -> m
m |> plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+expand_limits(x=5)
m |> simulate("Moran",time=2) -> m
m |> plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+expand_limits(x=5)
m |> simulate("Moran",time=3) -> m
m |> plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+expand_limits(x=5)
m |> simulate("Moran",time=4) -> m
m |> plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+expand_limits(x=5)
m |> simulate("Moran",time=5) -> m
m |> plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+expand_limits(x=5)

In the plots, the black dots correspond to extant lineages. Green dots demarcate the coalescence events (branch points). Brown dots denote the roots of the genealogical trees.

Animating the Moran genealogy process

An animation gives a better sense of the nature of the genealogy process. The following codes repeatedly continue and plot the simulation, storing the result as a list, pl, of plots.

simulate("Moran",t0=0,time=0,n=10,psi=0) -> m
times <- seq(0,10,by=0.1)
pl <- vector(mode="list",length=length(times))
for (i in seq_along(times)) {
  m |> simulate("Moran",time=times[i]) -> m
  m |>
    plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+
    expand_limits(x=10) -> pl[[i]]
}

In the following chunk, the sourced script defines the animator function. This constructs animations in one or more commonly used formats. You can view these files using a web browser or other software you have installed on your system. In an Rstudio session, you can also do file.show("moran1.gif") to display the animation.

source("https://kingaa.github.io/serrapilheira/phylo/animator.R")
animator(plots=pl,gif_file="figs/moran1.gif",webm=TRUE,mp4=TRUE)

Exercise

Explore the effect of changing the population size, \(n\). Be sure to run the simulations long enough so that the population has a unique common ancestor. How does this affect the time it takes for the whole population to reach this state? How does it affect the shape of the tree?

Linear birth-death process

Another class of approaches to phylodynamic inference is based on the linear birth-death process (Stadler 2010). In this model, a population of \(n_t\) individuals evolves according to the simplest possible demography: individuals give birth at rate \(\lambda\) and die at rate \(\mu\).

Importantly, in this model, the population size is no longer constant: even if \(\lambda=\mu\), \(n_t\) will fluctuate stochastically. In particular, the population will go extinct with probablity 1, though if \(\lambda>\mu\), it will become very large before it is extinguished, with nonzero probability. Indeed, the expected population size grows (or decays) exponentially in time: \(\mathbb{E}\left[{n_t}\;\middle\vert\;{n_0}\right]=n_0\,e^{(\lambda-\mu)\,t}\).

Following Stadler (2010), we allow for constant-rate sampling in this process. Specifically, each lineage is sampled at a rate \(\psi\). These samples are indicated as blue dots in the genealogical trees.

The linear birth-death genealogy process is implemented in phylopomp. Executing ?lbdp reveals the following.

Without sampling

As before, we can generate animations to visualize the linear birth-death genealogy process. First, we show a simulation without sampling. In the following, the RNG seed is carefully controlled, ensuring that, in this realization, the population does not die out immediately.

bake(
  seed=239863857,
  file="lbdp1.rds",
  {
    simulate("LBDP",t0=0,time=0,n=1,lambda=1.8,mu=1,psi=0) -> bd
    times <- seq(0,10,by=0.1)
    pl <- vector(mode="list",length=length(times))
    for (i in seq_along(times)) {
      bd |> simulate("LBDP",time=times[i]) -> bd
      bd |>
        plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+
        expand_limits(x=10) -> pl[[i]]
    }
    animator(plots=pl,gif_file="figs/lbdp1.gif",webm=TRUE,mp4=TRUE)
  }
)

With sampling

Now we introduce sampling, by making \(\psi>0\).

bake(
  seed=1282680647,
  file="lbdp2.rds",
  {
    simulate("LBDP",t0=0,time=0,n=1,lambda=1.4,mu=1,psi=0.5) -> bd
    times <- seq(0,10,by=0.1)
    pl <- vector(mode="list",length=length(times))
    for (i in seq_along(times)) {
      bd |> simulate("LBDP",time=times[i]) -> bd
      bd |>
        plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+
        expand_limits(x=10) -> pl[[i]]
    }
    animator(plots=pl,gif_file="figs/lbdp2.gif",webm=TRUE,mp4=TRUE)
  }
)

The pruned linear birth-death-sampling genealogy process

To prune the genealogy, is to discard all unsampled lineages. The following shows the same process as above, with pruning.

bake(
  seed=1282680647,
  file="lbdp3.rds",
  {
    simulate("LBDP",t0=0,time=0,n=1,lambda=1.4,mu=1,psi=0.5) -> bd
    times <- seq(0,10,by=0.1)
    pl <- vector(mode="list",length=length(times))
    for (i in seq_along(times)) {
      bd |> simulate("LBDP",time=times[i]) -> bd
      bd |>
        plot(prune=TRUE,points=TRUE)+
        expand_limits(x=10) -> pl[[i]]
    }
    animator(plots=pl,gif_file="figs/lbdp3.gif",webm=TRUE,mp4=TRUE)
  }
)

Exercise

A convenient feature of the linear birth-death genealogy process (and the reason for its widespread use in phylodynamic inference) is its self-similarity. Any subtree is statistically identical to any other subtree, and to the tree as a whole. Look for this property in snapshots of simulations.

SIR process

The first model that has the key features of a real disease-transmission process is the SIR genealogy process. This is the genealogy process induced by the simple SIR model.

The uniformly-sampled version of this model is implemented in phylopomp. Executing ?sir reveals the following.

Without sampling

bake(
  seed=1282680647,
  file="sir1.rds",
  {
    simulate(
      "SIR",t0=0,time=0,
      S0=200,I0=3,R0=0,
      Beta=2,gamma=1,psi=0
    ) -> sir
    times <- seq(0,10,by=0.1)
    pl <- vector(mode="list",length=length(times))
    for (i in seq_along(times)) {
      sir |> simulate("SIR",time=times[i]) -> sir
      sir |>
        plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+
        expand_limits(x=10) -> pl[[i]]
    }
    animator(plots=pl,gif_file="figs/sir1.gif",webm=TRUE,mp4=TRUE)
  }
)

With sampling

bake(
  seed=1282680647,
  file="sir2.rds",
  {
    simulate(
      "SIR",t0=0,time=0,
      S0=200,I0=3,R0=0,
      Beta=2,gamma=1,psi=0.2
    ) -> sir
    times <- seq(0,10,by=0.1)
    pl <- vector(mode="list",length=length(times))
    for (i in seq_along(times)) {
      sir |> simulate("SIR",time=times[i]) -> sir
      sir |>
        plot(prune=FALSE,points=TRUE)+
        expand_limits(x=10) -> pl[[i]]
    }
    animator(plots=pl,gif_file="figs/sir2.gif",webm=TRUE,mp4=TRUE)
  }
)
